                        Harriman
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d757</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">757</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-08-24T13:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-08-24T13:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-24T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-24T13:00:00-05:00" n="757" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d757">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 PW/8–2445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-24T21:00:00+03:00">August 24, 1945—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 24—8:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3045. <hi rend="italic">Red Fleet</hi> August 23 contains first mention Soviet
                    press since Soviet occupation Manchuria of “Chinese National Flag”, reporting it
                    raised over Fuyuan, near Khabarovsk first time many years. Harbin crowds shouted
                    “Hurrah” for Soviet and “Chinese peoples”.</p>
                <p>These brief references were overshadowed by descriptions of gratitude to Russians
                    and Stalin<note n="63" xml:id="d757fn63">Marshal Iosif Vissarionovich Stalin,
                        Chairman of the Council of Commissars (Premier) of the Soviet Union.</note>
                    whose portrait displayed most prominently. (Sent Department, repeated Chungking
                    109). No mention Chiang Kai-shek.<note n="64" xml:id="d757fn64">Generalissimo
                        and President of the National Government of the Republic of China.</note>
                    Conclusion one story reported people shout “Thank you, Stalin”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
